Total above ground sqft with garage: 5,568.42sqft. ***Compensating Factors: Credit Score: 706. Borrower never pays late. This is a good deal and a good area; the borrower is about to receive the building permit which adds additional equity/value. Borrowers Track Record: This loan is for a frequent WCP borrower, whose high-level experience includes fix and flips, additions to add sqft, and new constructions successfully sold. Experience in the last 3 years is 5 projects completed (sold), there''s 1 recently finished about to be listed. In total, borrower has completed 19 deals (5 active projects which are making consistent progress).  *** Loan structure: Purchase price $475k + Reno $900k = Total Cost $1,375,000 x LTC 75% = $1,031,250 Loan

nexrm_valuationcomments: Repeat Tier 2 WCP borrower, 739 FICO and tons of experience. Borrower has developed hundreds of units including a handful of 30-60 unit buildings in DC. He also does ground up new builds. Borrower got the property completed ground up and leased it. He struggled with a difficult tenant but eventually got them evicted. the property needed additional repairs as a result of that tenant, which borrower covered out of pocket. Since then he leased the property again and needs a runway to get the loan taken out with long term debt using a local bank he has a relationship with. Borrower brought his brother in as a partner, who also builds new builds in NVA. Borrower does not want to go through the extension process and feels it is more expensive. We are being extreme conservative on the values. Most comps are smaller than the subject property. It is likely worth $2.3mm today, but worst case $2,155,000 which is still 64.9% As-Is LTV. The loan is well protected at $1.4mm.

nexrm_wcpconditions: The loan shall include the following: $4,029,277 of construction hard cost draws, $390,000 of soft cost draws, $475,000 Interest Reserve, and ~$100,000 toward closing costs and points (placeholder). Interest shall not accrue on construction funds until they are drawn out. The loan is contingent upon a FICO of 680+, as-is value of $2,973,950 and ARV value of $9,000,000.
nexrm_valuationcomments: Borrower and his two adult children run a family Pharmacy chain business with many locations and are developers. The father has dementia and so the two sons run his business and have a court ordered conservatorship in place to make all decisions. The loan will be made to the father and the two sons. They also own a rental portfolio. They purchased the subject property 15 years ago and rented it more most of that time, before starting work to develop the land. They have obtained plans/permits and have it shovel ready. The property is owned free and clear. They seek a construction only loan to cover closing costs, soft and hard costs and an Interest Reserve. In addition to their experience with developing ground up projects, they have hired a contractor to assist with the project. The GC has experience building many large ground up apartment/condo complexes throughout the city, including several large hotels. We have obtained his resume and list of completed projects. WCP has lent to him on several projects and feel confident in his ability to complete the project, which is much smaller than what he has done. Property is owned free and clear, estimated at $2,973,950 as-is value. Soft costs to debt are $250k. Soft costs remaining to be financed are $390k plus $4,029,277 hard construction costs. It is shovel ready and has plans/permits for 11 units, but borrower will be requesting a revision to take one of the units and make it two given the size. Based on 12 units WCP projects $9mm exit. Urbanpace has an ARV of $10,088,800. Parking is another $240,000. FICO estimated at 680+ from all members. Loan includes $4,029,277 + $390,000 in construction draws, $475,000 Interest Reserve account, $100,000 toward closing costs/points (placeholder). Day one funding of $100k. As-is LTV = 3.4%. LTC = $4,994,277 / $6,919,277 (using current land value as ''purchase price'') = 72%. ARLTV = $4,994,277 / $9,720,000 = 51.4%.

nexrm_valuationcomments: Borrower purchased the property for $585k and took an acquisition + construction loan with WCP in the amount of $825,000. Borrower had plans prior to settlement but needed permits. He obtained permits during the original loan which took a much of the loan term. He then built the house ground up through MEP spending $557,450. Borrower never took a single draw and spent the money out of pocket. Borrower has excellent credit and is at least a Tier 2 borrower with ground up experience. Borrower reached the maturity date and was upset at the prospect of having to pay extension fees, so he paid off the loan with cash. He realized ~30 days later that he should have just extended and he didn''t want to put any more cash in the deal, so he reached back out to get a much smaller loan to finish the construction. The new loan is only $410,000 to cover the remaining draws of $400k and $10k toward closing costs. Our loan will be $10k against $585k buy + $557,450 construction spent to date ($1,142,450) = 1% as-is LTV. This is a very low basis. $410k / $1,675,000 appraised = 24% ARLTV. We actually project this will trade for $1.8mm as there was one recently several doors down that did at that same price with less desirable finishes. This will make the ARLTV even lower. $410k / $1,552,450 total cost = 26.4% LTC. This is the reason for the 1.5% points as we have already collected points on this loan once before. Very low risk given borrower has cash and will just pay the loan off worst case.

nexrm_wcpconditions: WCP is doing a refinance on this property to get cash out for another construction project borrower is working on. The current debt amount is $404,661.22, which will be paid off so WCP is in 1st Position. The remaining funds of $195,338.78 will go to cover closing costs. points and will be used as down payment for Borrower''s other construction project. The loan is subject to a 700+ FICO score and as-is value of $1,000,000. There shall be no cash out, but rather funds shall go to the HUD-1 of the other construction loan closing.
nexrm_valuationcomments: Borrower is doing this refinance along with 4912 and 4920 Nash St NE. This is one of the properties he currently owns and would be looking to get cash out for down payment on the 4920 Nash construction project. Experienced borrower with similar scoped projects and 747 FICO. Borrower purchased this 8 unit for $501,000 on 8/30/16. He renovated it for $250,000 and got 7 of the 8 units leased (88% occupancy). The as-is appraised value is $1,080,000. Current debt is $404,661.22. The loan breaks down as $404,661.22 toward existing debt, $195,338.78 cash toward the down payment of the new 4920 Nash project (borrower never touches this, it goes directly to the HUD of 4920) and $91,200 of cash out for operating capital. Closing costs are reduced from the proceeds. The Colchis guidelines allow for loans on multifamily properties with 740+ fico, tier 2 at 65% LTV. This loan is 64% LTV. This is smaller than Colchis'' current bridge loan on 4920 Nash of $747,500 for reference.

The final bed bath count will be 4 / 3. The project is through trades and she is preparing drywall. Borrower will list this property for sale once complete. No assignments or issues with last trade. $395,000 + $143,500 = $538,500 total cost = 84.9% LTC. This is a mid-reno refinance. Along with this loan we are agreeing to do a $12,275 unrecorded personal loan attached to her entity Barr None Investments LLC via promissory note, to be paid off by any of the loans that are paid off, not just 36th St. The loan will be priced at 12% and 3 points. We structured it this way to keep the loan at 85% LTC and keep it as a light rehab, lastly to keep the LTV lower. The personal loan shall only be 6 months in term. This was discussed and approved during the presale meeting. As this was purchased more recently than 2 years we must use the LTC metric.

nexrm_valuationcomments: Borrower is doing this refinance along with 4912 and 4916 Nash St NE. WCP did a bridge loan in the amount of $747,500 (it is a 4 unit apartment building). At the time of settlement 11/17/2021 it appraised for $1,150,000. Borrower purchased the property in 2018, completed the renovation of $300k and started leasing up the 4 units. He had 3 of the 4 leased when he came to us. Since then he leased the 4th unit. He then obtained stamped plans, BZA approval and is finalizing permits to build a ground up building immediately behind the existing structure to be connected by a walkway. This new building would be 8 units with 3 bd/2ba each. He determined he could build the structure more cost effectively this way rather than try to expand on the existing units square footage. He could also keep all 4 current tenants in place and keep generating rent without disrupting them. To facilitate this construction loan on 4920 Nash, he will need additional capital. Rather than raising investor funds or depleting his operating capital designated for running his rental portfolio, he seeks a cash out refi on two other properties immediately adjacent (4912 and 4916). $390,677.56 is coming from both properties towards the down payment. Borrower will cover the difference. All properties will be cross collateralized to use the equity to further reduce the risk. He is an experienced borrower with similar scoped projects in his track record and 747 FICO. The updated as-is value came back at $1mm from a different appraiser and is believed to be between $1m - $1.15m. The new loan is $1,560,000 with a $1,200,000 budget, leaving a day one principal balance of $360,000. Borrower is thus lowering the loan from $747,500 to $360,000. This is 36% as-is LTV and 46% ARLTV based on the appraised ARV of $3,375,000. We underwrote it conservatively at $2,400,000, which is still 65% ARLTV. Borrower is also hiring well know GC Harbor Builders who have an extensive multifamily portfolio of builds in the DMV.

WCP then did a ground up loan for him at 1433 Howard Rd SE. This was sold to Colchis, who bought it given borrower had completed several heavy rehab, nearly ground up projects. Borrower reached the maturity date of our 1433 Howard Rd SE loan having taken much longer to get permits then expected. He decided to pay it off given the loan was only construction draws so there was nothing to pay off. During the process of obtaining plans and permits DCRA required that he update the postal address, so 1433 Howard became 1431 1/2 Howard. He now has plans and permits. Borrower has a 782 FICO and is a Tier 2 borrower with heavy rehab experience. He does not have a ground up new build on his track record. There are no assignment fees or issues with last trade amount. Per the tax records borrower bought the lot in 2020 for $223,500. Borrower is building the house for $305,000. We are funding closing costs and the construction to remain sub 75% LTC. We can use the as-is value given when he bought the property (was greater than 2 years ago). $150,000 as-is value + $305,000 construction = $455,000 total cost. $325,000 / $455,000 = 71% LTC. While borrower doesn''t have a ground up property on his track record, he has completed several heavy renovations where most of the buildings were demo''d and rebuilt. He also has plans/permits so he can start day one. Lastly the LTC/as-is LTV is much lower than the usual 75% we require, which helps to off set some of the risk. Note, the value can go down to $505,000 and still maintain this loan at 65% ARLTV so there is room. We feel it will trade for more.

nexrm_valuationcomments: Repeat Tier 2 WCP Borrower with 728 FICO purchased the property on 8/29/2022, obtained plans and permits and have since made great progress. They are running into their 12-month maturity date with their current lender and looking at their options. The current lender is fine with extending the loan, but borrower isn''t happy with the cost of the extension. Today they have completed all demo, structural, foundation/underpinning, fully framed up the building with a roof, windows installed, doors installed, electrical meter bank on site, HVAC materials on site, and plumbing materials on site to be installed in the next 2-3 weeks. Projected rough-in inspection and hanging drywall in mid-September. Project delivery in 6 months, with 6 months for unit sales. Borrower has spent $100,000 on soft costs to obtain plans/permits, and $300,000 on hard costs plus the most recent construction drawn of $109,508.76 for a total of $409,508.76. When he brought the deal the payoff statement was $962,591.24, but he kept working and was eligible for another draw in the amount of $109,508.76. The payoff statement today stands at $1,072,100. We will be keeping the originally agreed upon loan of $1,528,000 in place. This will cover the $1,072,100 payoff and remaining construction draws of $650,000 - $109,508.76 = $540,491.24. Borrower will bring closing costs and points at settlement. Note this project does have a commercial retail ground floor unit. As a result of its midreno and commercial unit status we presold it to 1Sharpe. The LTC calculation is $100k + $409,508.76 + $540,491.24 + $882,500 buy ($860,000 not including assignment fee) = $1,932,500 total cost. $1,528,000 loan amount / $1,932,500 = 79.1% LTC. $1,528,000 / $2,500,000 ARV = 61.1% ARLTV.

nexrm_valuationcomments: This borrower has successfully completed one project with WCP (closed and paid off 1/24). He has a total of 7 projects that he''s worked on and he''s a very good contractor. He has worked on other WCP clients projects and also managed his dads investment properties before starting his own. He has a high credit score of 753. This property is in Hughesville MD which is a smaller town but it''s only 10 miles from La Plata. Very good location in Charles County less than an hour from DC. This property was purchased for $220,000 in June of 2022 but the wholesaler/investor who purchased it already put about $90,000 of work into the project to increase the As-is value. We have pictures showing the progress. It only requires $30,000 more of rehab and about 2 months tops to get it on market. The investor is selling it only because his crews are tied up on 10 other projects at the moment (3 of which were just picked up in December). The loan will be at 12% and 2.5 points and we''re basing it

nexrm_valuationcomments: This is an 80% 1st trust within Colchis guidelines  for a repeat client with 10 deals in the last 3 years with 2 of them being new builds. Borrower is purchasing this property for well below market value and complete cosmetic renovation to put back on market in the spring for profit. There is an assignment fee of 38k of which we are only crediting 15% or $17,550 for the first trust. There is a second trust of $25,720 for a total loan of $189,360. below 70% LTV. our total loan is based on 90% of the total project cost with crediting 20% of the assignment fee

nexrm_valuationcomments: **1st DOT info: LTC 85% acquisition plus renovation loan for experienced, active, frequent WCP borrower. The borrower''s high level experience includes fix and flips, additions to add sqft, and new constructions succesfully sold. Experience in the last 3 years experience includes 6 projects (sold). In total, we have financed 22 deals (18 paid off, 4 active projects which are making consistent progress of course). Check out the quality on the last project sold on 12/02/22, click on link for pics: https://www.zillow.com/homedetails/1733-Independence-Ave-SE-Washington-DC-20003/427001_zpid/ ). Note that borrower is highly bankable, very responsive and never pays late. ***DEAL INFO: The borrower found a great deal which appraised higher than the purchase price. The seller''s husband passed away and she wants to get rid of it. *LOAN STRUCTURE: Purchase price $385k + Reno $90k = Total Cost $475k x LTC 85% = $403,750 Loan. (Note: The construction/renovation at 90k, is 22.29% of the loan amount). ****2nd DOT structure at LTC 5%: Purchase price $385k + Reno $90k = Total Cost $475k x LTC 5% = $23,750 Loan. Asking for a 12 month loan. (Note: 1st DOT ARV LTV% is 69.37%, the 2nd ARV LTV% is 4.08%. Combined ARV LTV% is 73.45%, for a total LTC of 90%)
